---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
---
<Layout title="Tax Glossary - New Zealand Payroll Terms Explained | TakeHomePay.nz" description="A comprehensive glossary of New Zealand payroll and tax terms including PAYE, KiwiSaver, ACC Levy, student loan repayment, and more.">
  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify({
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "BreadcrumbList",
    "itemListElement": [
      { "@type": "ListItem", "position": 1, "name": "Home", "item": "https://takehomepay.nz/" },
      { "@type": "ListItem", "position": 2, "name": "Glossary", "item": "https://takehomepay.nz/glossary/" }
    ]
  })} />

  <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-4 py-8">
    <nav class="text-sm text-gray-500 mb-6">
      <a href="/" class="hover:text-primary">Home</a>
      <span class="mx-2">/</span>
      <span class="text-gray-800">Glossary</span>
    </nav>

    <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-4">New Zealand Tax and Payroll Glossary</h1>
    <p class="text-gray-600 mb-8">A reference guide to the key terms you will encounter on your New Zealand payslip, tax return, and when using our salary calculator. Understanding these terms will help you take control of your finances. Terms are listed in alphabetical order.</p>

    <dl class="space-y-6">
      <div>
        <dt class="text-lg font-semibold text-gray-900">ACC Levy (Accident Compensation Corporation Levy)</dt>
        <dd class="text-gray-700 mt-1 leading-relaxed">The ACC earners' levy is a compulsory contribution paid by all New Zealand earners to fund the Accident Compensation Corporation scheme. ACC provides no-fault personal injury cover for all New Zealand residents and visitors. The earners' levy is deducted from your pay by your employer and is calculated as a percentage of your liable earnings up to a maximum. The levy rate is set annually by ACC and is typically around 1.39% to 1.60% of gross earnings.</dd>
      </div>

      <div>
        <dt class="text-lg font-semibold text-gray-900">Employer Contribution (KiwiSaver)</dt>
        <dd class="text-gray-700 mt-1 leading-relaxed">When you contribute to KiwiSaver, your employer is required to make a minimum compulsory contribution of 3% of your gross salary. This employer contribution is on top of your own employee contribution and is paid directly into your KiwiSaver fund. The employer contribution is subject to Employer Superannuation Contribution Tax (ESCT), which is deducted before the money reaches your KiwiSaver account.</dd>
      </div>

      <div>
        <dt class="text-lg font-semibold text-gray-900">Gross Income</dt>
        <dd class="text-gray-700 mt-1 leading-relaxed">Gross income is your total earnings before any deductions are applied. It includes your base salary, wages, overtime pay, bonuses, commissions, and other taxable income. Gross income is the starting point for calculating PAYE tax, KiwiSaver contributions, ACC levy, and student loan repayments. Your employment agreement typically states your salary in gross terms.</dd>
      </div>

      <div>
        <dt class="text-lg font-semibold text-gray-900">GST (Goods and Services Tax)</dt>
        <dd class="text-gray-700 mt-1 leading-relaxed">GST is New Zealand's consumption tax, currently set at 15%. While GST is not deducted from your salary, it affects your purchasing power because it is applied to most goods and services you buy. Self-employed individuals and contractors may need to register for and collect GST if their turnover exceeds the registration threshold. Understanding GST is important for freelancers when quoting rates and managing invoicing.</dd>
      </div>

      <div>
        <dt class="text-lg font-semibold text-gray-900">Independent Earner Tax Credit (IETC)</dt>
        <dd class="text-gray-700 mt-1 leading-relaxed">The Independent Earner Tax Credit is a tax credit for New Zealand tax residents who earn between $24,000 and $70,000 per year and do not receive any income-tested government benefits, New Zealand Superannuation, or Working for Families tax credits. The maximum credit is $520 per year. The IETC is designed to provide a tax break to middle-income earners who do not receive other forms of government support.</dd>
      </div>

      <div>
        <dt class="text-lg font-semibold text-gray-900">IRD Number</dt>
        <dd class="text-gray-700 mt-1 leading-relaxed">An IRD number is a unique tax identification number issued by Inland Revenue New Zealand to every person and organization that pays or receives income in the country. You need an IRD number to start employment, open a bank account that earns interest, or file a tax return. Without an IRD number, your employer must deduct tax at the no-notification rate, which is the highest PAYE rate.</dd>
      </div>

      <div>
        <dt class="text-lg font-semibold text-gray-900">KiwiSaver</dt>
        <dd class="text-gray-700 mt-1 leading-relaxed">KiwiSaver is New Zealand's voluntary, work-based savings initiative designed to help people save for retirement. Employees can choose a contribution rate of 3%, 4%, 6%, 8%, or 10% of their gross salary. Contributions are deducted from your pay before you receive it. KiwiSaver funds are generally locked in until you reach the age of eligibility for New Zealand Superannuation (currently 65), though first-home buyers may be able to withdraw funds earlier.</dd>
      </div>

      <div>
        <dt class="text-lg font-semibold text-gray-900">PAYE (Pay As You Earn)</dt>
        <dd class="text-gray-700 mt-1 leading-relaxed">PAYE is the system through which income tax is deducted from your wages by your employer and paid to Inland Revenue on your behalf. New Zealand uses progressive tax rates: currently 10.5% on income up to $14,000, 17.5% from $14,001 to $48,000, 30% from $48,001 to $70,000, 33% from $70,001 to $180,000, and 39% on income over $180,000. The amount of PAYE deducted depends on your gross pay and your tax code.</dd>
      </div>

      <div>
        <dt class="text-lg font-semibold text-gray-900">PIE Tax (Portfolio Investment Entity Tax)</dt>
        <dd class="text-gray-700 mt-1 leading-relaxed">PIE tax is a tax on income earned through Portfolio Investment Entities, which include many KiwiSaver funds and managed investment funds. Your PIE income is taxed at your Prescribed Investor Rate (PIR), which can be 10.5%, 17.5%, or 28% depending on your total taxable income. PIE income taxed at the correct PIR does not need to be included in your income tax return, and any tax paid on PIE income is a final tax.</dd>
      </div>

      <div>
        <dt class="text-lg font-semibold text-gray-900">Provisional Tax</dt>
        <dd class="text-gray-700 mt-1 leading-relaxed">Provisional tax is a way of paying income tax in installments during the year rather than in a lump sum at the end of the tax year. It applies to self-employed individuals, contractors, and anyone with significant income that does not have PAYE deducted at source. If your residual income tax is above a set threshold, you are required to pay provisional tax. The standard method bases payments on your previous year's tax liability plus a 5% uplift.</dd>
      </div>

      <div>
        <dt class="text-lg font-semibold text-gray-900">Secondary Income</dt>
        <dd class="text-gray-700 mt-1 leading-relaxed">Secondary income is earnings from a second or additional job. In New Zealand, secondary income is taxed using a secondary tax code (such as S, SH, or ST), which applies a flat rate that approximates the marginal tax rate on your additional earnings. This ensures the correct amount of tax is collected across all your income sources, preventing a large tax bill at the end of the year.</dd>
      </div>

      <div>
        <dt class="text-lg font-semibold text-gray-900">Student Loan Repayment</dt>
        <dd class="text-gray-700 mt-1 leading-relaxed">If you have a New Zealand student loan from StudyLink, repayments are automatically deducted from your pay once your income exceeds the repayment threshold. The current repayment rate is 12% of every dollar earned above the threshold. Your employer deducts these repayments through the PAYE system when you use a tax code that includes the "SL" suffix. Student loan repayments reduce your take-home pay but do not attract interest for New Zealand-based borrowers.</dd>
      </div>

      <div>
        <dt class="text-lg font-semibold text-gray-900">Tax Code</dt>
        <dd class="text-gray-700 mt-1 leading-relaxed">Your tax code tells your employer how much PAYE to deduct from your pay. The most common code is "M" for a primary job with no student loan. Other codes include "ME" (primary job with student loan), "S" (secondary job), "SH" (secondary job, higher rate), and "CAE" (casual agricultural worker). Choosing the correct tax code is important to avoid over- or under-payment of tax throughout the year.</dd>
      </div>

      <div>
        <dt class="text-lg font-semibold text-gray-900">Taxable Income</dt>
        <dd class="text-gray-700 mt-1 leading-relaxed">Taxable income is the portion of your gross income that is subject to income tax after any allowable deductions. For most salary and wage earners, taxable income is the same as gross income because New Zealand has limited personal deductions. However, self-employed individuals can deduct legitimate business expenses. Taxable income is the figure to which PAYE tax rates are applied to determine your tax liability.</dd>
      </div>

      <div>
        <dt class="text-lg font-semibold text-gray-900">Working for Families</dt>
        <dd class="text-gray-700 mt-1 leading-relaxed">Working for Families is a package of tax credits designed to help families with dependent children who are on low to middle incomes. It includes the Family Tax Credit, In-Work Tax Credit, Minimum Family Tax Credit, and Best Start Tax Credit. Eligibility and amounts depend on your family's combined income, the number of children, and their ages. Working for Families payments are administered by Inland Revenue and can be received as a lump sum or in regular payments throughout the year.</dd>
      </div>
    </dl>
  </div>
</Layout>
